    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="1300"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1300">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 855.48/28</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HMT1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Herrick</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Paris</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-05">
                        <hi rend="italic">November 5, 1914</hi>
                    </date>, <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11:45 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>248. Your 221 and 231, 31st and 4th respectively. This matter immediately
                    referred to Bordeaux where Foreign Office replied that matter had already been
                    taken up with British Government and would advise Embassy what decision the two
                    Governments had reached. <persName corresp="#p_GJW2" type="from"
                        >Garrett</persName> advises by telephone this afternoon has had no answer
                    yet.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HMT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Herrick</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
